WEBVTT

1
00:00:06.000 --> 00:00:12.074
Support us and become VIP member 
to remove all ads from www.OpenSubtitles.org

2
00:00:38.280 --> 00:00:42.273
Letters From Iwo Jima

3
00:00:52.000 --> 00:00:55.515
IWO JIMA

4
00:02:03.720 --> 00:02:07.076
How did those soldiers ever manage
to dig out these tunnels?

5
00:02:07.920 --> 00:02:09.273
Let's get a rotation in here.

6
00:02:09.440 --> 00:02:11.237
Hey. I found something!

7
00:02:22.840 --> 00:02:25.479
IWO JIMA

8
00:02:25.640 --> 00:02:26.709
Hanako...

9
00:02:27.640 --> 00:02:29.471
We soldiers dig.

10
00:02:29.960 --> 00:02:32.520
We dig all day.

11
00:02:34.440 --> 00:02:36.431
<i>This is the hole that we will fight...</i>

12
00:02:37.200 --> 00:02:38.872
and die in.

13
00:02:41.120 --> 00:02:42.519
Hanako...

14
00:02:43.040 --> 00:02:46.157
am I digging my own grave?

15
00:03:18.520 --> 00:03:21.910
<i>Today. I head for the post
where my men await.</i>

16
00:03:22.760 --> 00:03:26.799
I am determined to serve
and give my life for my country.

17
00:03:27.880 --> 00:03:30.314
<i>I believe I have organized
everything at home...</i>

18
00:03:30.480 --> 00:03:34.917
but I am sorry I wasn 't able to attend
to the kitchen floor before I left.

19
00:03:35.560 --> 00:03:37.278
I had all the intention...

20
00:03:37.440 --> 00:03:39.670
but had to leave
without having the time...

21
00:03:40.080 --> 00:03:42.071
and I am still worried about it.

22
00:03:42.320 --> 00:03:45.312
<i>So make sure to have
Taro take care of it promptly.</i>

23
00:03:51.160 --> 00:03:54.948
Damn this island!
The Americans can have it.

24
00:03:57.320 --> 00:03:58.594
Nothing grows here.

25
00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:04.355
It smells. It's hot. There are too many
damn bugs. and there's no water.

26
00:04:06.560 --> 00:04:10.189
This island is part
of Japan's sacred homeland.

27
00:04:10.480 --> 00:04:12.471
There's nothing sacred about this island.

28
00:04:15.880 --> 00:04:16.995
Saigo.

29
00:04:17.400 --> 00:04:21.075
We should just give the island
to the Americans. . .

30
00:04:21.320 --> 00:04:22.719
and then we can go home.

31
00:04:26.120 --> 00:04:27.189
Saigo!

32
00:04:28.960 --> 00:04:30.234
What did you say. soldier?

33
00:04:31.840 --> 00:04:35.150
I said if we beat the Americans.
then we can go home.

34
00:04:36.280 --> 00:04:38.316
You there. is that what he said?

35
00:04:39.720 --> 00:04:41.915
Yes. sir.

36
00:06:01.360 --> 00:06:02.395
I'm Kuribayashi.

37
00:06:02.600 --> 00:06:05.160
Welcome. General.
I am Admiral Ohsugi.

38
00:06:05.520 --> 00:06:07.750
How long have you been
waiting here for me?

39
00:06:08.840 --> 00:06:10.159
Three hours. sir.

40
00:06:10.320 --> 00:06:11.594
Sorry to hear that.

41
00:06:11.800 --> 00:06:13.995
They wouldn't allow me
to wire my arrival. . .

42
00:06:14.160 --> 00:06:16.151
after what happened
to Admiral Yamamoto.

43
00:06:16.400 --> 00:06:17.469
I understand. sir.

44
00:06:17.720 --> 00:06:19.517
This is my aide. Lieutenant Fujita.

45
00:06:20.120 --> 00:06:22.509
What's the matter. Admiral?
You don't look very well.

46
00:06:22.720 --> 00:06:25.917
It's nothing. sir. The water
doesn't agree with me here.

47
00:06:26.080 --> 00:06:27.513
Sorry to hear that.

48
00:06:28.160 --> 00:06:29.593
This way to your quarters.

49
00:06:29.880 --> 00:06:32.348
Admiral. I want to make a round
of the island first.

50
00:06:32.560 --> 00:06:34.516
Shall I fetch a vehicle?

51
00:06:34.680 --> 00:06:36.557
No. let's walk.

52
00:06:37.520 --> 00:06:39.078
Walking is good for the health.

53
00:06:39.240 --> 00:06:41.310
It might be just what you need. Ohsugi.

54
00:06:56.600 --> 00:06:58.272
So that's Suribachi.

55
00:07:06.960 --> 00:07:07.995
You unpatriotic. . .

56
00:07:08.680 --> 00:07:09.954
no-good peasants!

57
00:07:10.400 --> 00:07:11.594
Hey. stop it!

58
00:07:15.200 --> 00:07:16.235
Stand up!

59
00:07:17.200 --> 00:07:18.519
What are you doing?

60
00:07:21.120 --> 00:07:22.394
These soldiers. . .

61
00:07:25.120 --> 00:07:27.031
were conspiring
with unpatriotic words. sir.

62
00:07:28.040 --> 00:07:29.109
I see.

63
00:07:29.360 --> 00:07:31.874
And. Captain. do you have
such an excess of soldiers. . .

64
00:07:32.040 --> 00:07:34.554
that you could put two
of them out of commission?

65
00:07:35.440 --> 00:07:36.589
No. sir.

66
00:07:37.480 --> 00:07:39.038
Then stop beating them.

67
00:07:39.400 --> 00:07:41.595
Deny their lunch rations instead.

68
00:07:42.120 --> 00:07:45.669
A good captain uses his brain.
not just his whip.

69
00:07:50.440 --> 00:07:52.112
What is all this?

70
00:07:52.720 --> 00:07:53.869
All this?

71
00:07:54.160 --> 00:07:55.388
Trenches. sir.

72
00:07:56.080 --> 00:07:57.752
Why are the men digging trenches here?

73
00:07:58.280 --> 00:08:00.999
This is where the Americans
are expected to land.

74
00:08:02.760 --> 00:08:04.432
Have them stop immediately.

75
00:08:05.200 --> 00:08:06.553
But. General--

76
00:08:07.160 --> 00:08:08.309
And. Captain. . .

77
00:08:09.120 --> 00:08:11.031
make sure these men get proper breaks.

78
00:08:11.360 --> 00:08:13.715
They look like they're from Mars.

79
00:08:25.920 --> 00:08:27.114
Stop digging!

80
00:08:43.880 --> 00:08:45.154
Just as well.

81
00:08:46.320 --> 00:08:49.039
My stomach has been
bothering me anyway.

82
00:08:50.200 --> 00:08:52.316
A toast to General Kuribayashi. . .

83
00:08:53.960 --> 00:08:55.552
a fine commander.

84
00:08:59.400 --> 00:09:00.992
Better than sake!

85
00:09:01.800 --> 00:09:03.472
I heard he lived in America.

86
00:09:04.640 --> 00:09:06.995
Maybe that's why he
doesn't want us digging trenches.

87
00:09:07.160 --> 00:09:08.798
Maybe he likes Americans.

88
00:09:09.040 --> 00:09:12.476
No. stupid.
He studied the Americans.

89
00:09:14.400 --> 00:09:17.153
So now he knows how to beat them.

90
00:09:18.800 --> 00:09:20.518
I heard from someone in the 204th. . .

91
00:09:21.240 --> 00:09:25.597
that another general was
supposed to command the island. . .

92
00:09:26.280 --> 00:09:29.272
but he didn't want the job.

93
00:09:30.680 --> 00:09:34.559
So Premier Tojo gave it
to Kuribayashi instead.

94
00:09:35.880 --> 00:09:39.634
Nozaki. you hear a lot of things. . .

95
00:09:41.000 --> 00:09:43.070
but your ears are full of wax!

96
00:09:44.680 --> 00:09:48.559
Anyway. you can't trust anyone
from the 204th.

97
00:09:48.720 --> 00:09:50.517
They're part of the Navy.

98
00:09:50.840 --> 00:09:53.718
I think this Kuribayashi
must be a superb general.

99
00:09:54.240 --> 00:09:55.389
Look. . .

100
00:09:56.120 --> 00:10:01.194
we're not digging those damn trenches
in the sand anymore. are we?

101
00:10:17.040 --> 00:10:19.918
This heat is more than I had anticipated.

102
00:10:24.480 --> 00:10:29.315
This island is bigger than I thought.
I'm exhausted.

103
00:10:36.640 --> 00:10:37.755
Ito. reporting for duty.

104
00:10:37.920 --> 00:10:39.876
Thank you for coming right away.

105
00:10:41.080 --> 00:10:43.594
How much air force
do we have available?

106
00:10:43.760 --> 00:10:46.228
41 Zekes and 13 bombers. sir.

107
00:10:46.400 --> 00:10:47.389
Is that all?

108
00:10:47.560 --> 00:10:51.473
In order to support Saipan.
we lost 66 planes a few days ago.

109
00:10:52.720 --> 00:10:56.872
We will have to rely on support
from the Combined Fleet then.

110
00:10:59.160 --> 00:11:00.673
Is this the current defense plan?

111
00:11:06.160 --> 00:11:08.958
And what about the Army troops?
Where will they be stationed?

112
00:11:11.680 --> 00:11:13.477
I don't know exactly.

113
00:11:13.640 --> 00:11:16.393
They are under independent
command of Colonel Adachi.

114
00:11:16.560 --> 00:11:18.835
You have not coordinated
your plans with the Army?

115
00:11:19.000 --> 00:11:21.639
According to Navy rules.
until the enemy lands--

116
00:11:21.800 --> 00:11:24.598
This is a real war!
You are aware of that. aren't you?

117
00:11:30.480 --> 00:11:31.595
This will not work.

118
00:11:31.760 --> 00:11:34.115
You are concentrating all
your efforts on the beaches.

119
00:11:34.520 --> 00:11:37.592
- Move the artillery to higher ground.
- But. sir. we just had them. . .

120
00:11:37.760 --> 00:11:39.273
moved down to the beaches.

121
00:11:39.440 --> 00:11:40.839
Well. move them back.

122
00:11:43.120 --> 00:11:45.588
Coordinate with the Army
and have them start immediately.

123
00:11:45.760 --> 00:11:48.718
Fortifications at Suribachi are the priority.

124
00:11:49.160 --> 00:11:50.388
I'm going to walk some more.

125
00:11:50.600 --> 00:11:53.353
- It's pitch black out there. sir.
- I know.

126
00:12:03.920 --> 00:12:05.353
This one is trouble.

127
00:12:07.240 --> 00:12:10.437
Army commanders usually are. sir.

128
00:12:51.400 --> 00:12:52.719
Another letter?

129
00:12:52.920 --> 00:12:55.878
You know that the mail only goes out
when there's a boat available?

130
00:12:56.320 --> 00:12:57.673
I have a lot of family.

131
00:12:58.200 --> 00:13:00.873
Then how come all your letters
are addressed to your wife?

132
00:13:02.400 --> 00:13:03.515
Nosey!

133
00:13:03.720 --> 00:13:05.278
Here. let me do you a favor.

134
00:13:05.800 --> 00:13:08.837
Otherwise. your letters
will never make it through.

135
00:13:09.960 --> 00:13:11.598
Hey. what are you doing?

136
00:13:12.000 --> 00:13:15.310
I used to work at the censorship office
in Tokyo before I was transferred.

137
00:13:16.240 --> 00:13:17.958
You mean demoted.

138
00:13:18.880 --> 00:13:22.270
" To Hanako: We soldiers dig.
We dig all day. "

139
00:13:22.480 --> 00:13:25.040
No. no. no. This will never pass.

140
00:13:26.960 --> 00:13:28.473
Give me that back!

141
00:13:36.920 --> 00:13:41.118
There. You'll thank me
for this later. Saigo.

142
00:13:44.800 --> 00:13:45.915
Next!

143
00:13:52.160 --> 00:13:53.354
Good!

144
00:14:18.840 --> 00:14:20.353
Are you blind?

145
00:14:21.840 --> 00:14:23.558
Can't you see the target?

146
00:14:24.840 --> 00:14:28.037
Even my six-year-old could
shoot better than you do.

147
00:14:29.240 --> 00:14:30.309
Do it again!

148
00:14:36.120 --> 00:14:39.476
You're an embarrassment!
You call yourself an lmperial soldier?

149
00:14:41.320 --> 00:14:44.756
Tonight you will clean the boots
of your entire troop.

150
00:14:44.920 --> 00:14:45.955
Go to the rear!

151
00:14:48.360 --> 00:14:51.830
They should learn to clean their guns
properly. rather than their boots.

152
00:15:25.960 --> 00:15:27.712
What are those tanks doing here?

153
00:15:28.040 --> 00:15:31.874
Those are out of commission. sir.
They are waiting for parts.

154
00:15:32.080 --> 00:15:34.594
- For how long?
- About a month. sir.

155
00:15:53.640 --> 00:15:56.871
<i>Taro. America is filled with cars.</i>

156
00:15:57.960 --> 00:16:01.953
I have to be very careful
when I cross the street...

157
00:16:02.760 --> 00:16:05.228
there are so many cars everywhere.

158
00:16:06.240 --> 00:16:10.074
<i>Taro. are you behaving yourself
and listening to your mother?</i>

159
00:16:10.800 --> 00:16:12.358
I miss you.

160
00:16:22.000 --> 00:16:25.117
These civilians need to be
evacuated as soon as possible.

161
00:16:26.280 --> 00:16:27.952
Yes. sir.

162
00:17:26.760 --> 00:17:27.749
Hanako...

163
00:17:28.640 --> 00:17:30.471
we have a celebrity here.

164
00:17:31.040 --> 00:17:34.237
<i>Baron Nishi. the Olympic gold medalist
in horse jumping.</i>

165
00:17:35.600 --> 00:17:38.273
<i>He will lead the 26th tank regiment...</i>

166
00:17:38.920 --> 00:17:41.673
<i>and has just arrived from Tokyo.</i>

167
00:17:56.040 --> 00:18:00.033
<i>Nishi is very handsome. and there are
rumors of his womanizing skills.</i>

168
00:18:01.240 --> 00:18:05.313
But there are no women
left on the island to woo.

169
00:18:30.600 --> 00:18:33.512
Lieutenant Colonel Nishi!
You brought your horse.

170
00:18:34.080 --> 00:18:35.195
From Chichi Jima.

171
00:18:41.040 --> 00:18:43.031
I used to be a cavalryman myself.
you know.

172
00:18:43.200 --> 00:18:45.191
Of course. I know.

173
00:18:45.440 --> 00:18:48.716
I've been looking forward
to serving under you.

174
00:18:49.280 --> 00:18:51.669
One who understands horses
the way I do.

175
00:18:51.840 --> 00:18:55.833
When we used to ride horses
through the battlefield. . .

176
00:18:56.000 --> 00:18:57.797
those were the good old days. . .

177
00:18:59.160 --> 00:19:01.116
not like these mechanized contraptions.

178
00:19:02.400 --> 00:19:04.516
I could send for another horse. . .

179
00:19:05.360 --> 00:19:06.793
and we could ride together.

180
00:19:06.960 --> 00:19:08.552
I'm afraid my riding days are over.

181
00:19:10.080 --> 00:19:14.676
But tell me about this famous horse
of yours that you won the Olympics with.

182
00:19:15.520 --> 00:19:16.794
My stallion. Uranus.

183
00:19:27.720 --> 00:19:30.712
Oh. yes. this horse has a fine back.

184
00:19:34.160 --> 00:19:36.037
I bought him in Italy.

185
00:19:36.840 --> 00:19:38.751
They were happy to get rid of him.

186
00:19:38.920 --> 00:19:41.559
He was such a wild horse.

187
00:19:42.520 --> 00:19:46.638
No one could tame the beast.
but I told them. . .

188
00:19:46.800 --> 00:19:48.631
such a headstrong horse. . .

189
00:19:49.040 --> 00:19:52.271
is a perfect match for me.

190
00:19:56.480 --> 00:19:59.040
Come dine with me tonight.
I feel like having a drink.

191
00:19:59.920 --> 00:20:01.353
I think that can be arranged.

192
00:20:10.680 --> 00:20:12.989
How did you manage to get
the Johnnie Walker?

193
00:20:13.640 --> 00:20:15.312
I drank some already.

194
00:20:21.400 --> 00:20:24.073
I'm sorry. This is all we have.

195
00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:26.276
That's fine. as long as we have this.

196
00:20:30.400 --> 00:20:32.152
What is this empty plate?

197
00:20:33.280 --> 00:20:35.191
I have told our cook that all officers. . .

198
00:20:35.360 --> 00:20:37.590
will have the same rations
and food as our men.

199
00:20:37.760 --> 00:20:40.718
I'm sorry. but serving three dishes
is regulation.

200
00:20:41.720 --> 00:20:45.269
Oh. but of course we have the right to be
served more than three dishes per meal.

201
00:20:45.440 --> 00:20:46.634
You're absolutely right.

202
00:20:57.320 --> 00:20:59.072
When you think about it. . .

203
00:20:59.440 --> 00:21:03.558
it is regrettable that most of the
Combined Fleet was destroyed.

204
00:21:05.080 --> 00:21:06.752
We still have some battleships left. . .

205
00:21:06.920 --> 00:21:11.710
but we have very little striking power
from the air or sea.

206
00:21:12.800 --> 00:21:14.233
Nishi. what do you mean?

207
00:21:17.440 --> 00:21:21.877
So you have not heard about
the Mariana battle?

208
00:21:22.920 --> 00:21:27.710
Admiral Ozawa's carrier and boat planes
were destroyed.

209
00:21:30.200 --> 00:21:31.519
The lmperial headquarters. . .

210
00:21:32.160 --> 00:21:34.913
is deceiving not just the people.
but us as well.

211
00:21:35.320 --> 00:21:37.959
If you want my honest opinion. General. . .

212
00:21:39.600 --> 00:21:41.431
the best thing to do. . .

213
00:21:42.240 --> 00:21:46.597
would be to sink the island
to the bottom of the sea.

214
00:21:48.960 --> 00:21:50.757
And yet. you still came?

215
00:21:53.800 --> 00:21:54.835
Well. . .

216
00:21:55.240 --> 00:22:00.030
I figured your men were going to need
all the tanks that I could bring.

217
00:22:47.000 --> 00:22:48.399
This must be it.

218
00:22:48.800 --> 00:22:50.677
Yes. the enemy must land here.

219
00:22:55.920 --> 00:22:56.955
Run!

220
00:22:57.960 --> 00:22:59.518
Like you were one of the Americans!

221
00:22:59.720 --> 00:23:01.551
Go on! Which direction would you take?

222
00:23:29.280 --> 00:23:30.429
Hey. . .

223
00:23:31.520 --> 00:23:33.511
I think your general has gone mad.

224
00:23:37.320 --> 00:23:38.992
Look at the gun he has.

225
00:23:43.400 --> 00:23:46.278
He probably took it
from a dead American.

226
00:23:47.360 --> 00:23:48.713
Maybe.

227
00:23:56.480 --> 00:23:57.754
Break time is over.

228
00:23:58.440 --> 00:23:59.634
Back to work!

229
00:24:04.120 --> 00:24:05.758
Are you all right. Kashiwara?

230
00:24:06.320 --> 00:24:07.878
You look pale.

231
00:24:09.600 --> 00:24:11.591
I'm fine. It's just the damn water.

232
00:24:12.280 --> 00:24:15.909
But. . .I. . .really. . .need to go.

233
00:24:34.560 --> 00:24:36.676
There will be a major change
in our strategy.

234
00:24:37.320 --> 00:24:41.871
We will dig caves in the Motoyama.
Higashiyama. and Suribachi-yama areas.

235
00:24:42.400 --> 00:24:46.598
We will build these underground
fortifications. and fight to the end.

236
00:24:46.880 --> 00:24:49.952
- What about the beach defenses. sir?
- Not needed.

237
00:24:51.360 --> 00:24:54.909
But. sir. the beach trenches
are our first line of defense.

238
00:24:55.080 --> 00:24:58.311
Without the beach trenches.
how do you expect us to win?

239
00:24:58.480 --> 00:25:03.270
Hayashi. do you know how many cars
America produces in a year?

240
00:25:03.440 --> 00:25:04.555
Five million.

241
00:25:05.000 --> 00:25:07.958
The Americans' technological
advancements cannot be underestimated.

242
00:25:08.120 --> 00:25:10.793
They will cross the beaches eventually.

243
00:25:12.320 --> 00:25:14.709
If we waste our soldiers there.
there is no hope for victory.

244
00:25:14.880 --> 00:25:16.598
It is inevitable that men will die. . .

245
00:25:17.160 --> 00:25:20.277
but I never heard of an island operation
without beach fortifications.

246
00:25:20.440 --> 00:25:23.910
General. it will be a futile waste of time
to start digging tunnels now.

247
00:25:24.080 --> 00:25:25.638
We should force the enemy
near the island. . .

248
00:25:25.800 --> 00:25:27.870
and launch a pincer drive
from the sea and air.

249
00:25:28.040 --> 00:25:30.315
I agree. That makes the most sense.

250
00:25:30.520 --> 00:25:31.555
Ohsugi. . .

251
00:25:32.560 --> 00:25:34.198
doesn't the Navy know?

252
00:25:38.080 --> 00:25:41.436
The Combined Fleet has been completely
destroyed off the Marianas.

253
00:25:41.640 --> 00:25:43.631
The island is now isolated.

254
00:25:48.960 --> 00:25:52.509
What's more. I received a new order from
the lmperial headquarters this morning.

255
00:25:52.880 --> 00:25:55.189
The remaining fighter planes
are to be sent back. . .

256
00:25:55.360 --> 00:25:56.918
to Tokyo to defend the mainland.

257
00:25:57.080 --> 00:25:59.992
Outrageous! How are we to fight?

258
00:26:03.600 --> 00:26:07.354
We do not have time for discussion.
We should head back.

259
00:26:39.000 --> 00:26:40.115
<i>Dear Mother...</i>

260
00:26:41.680 --> 00:26:44.797
I have been commissioned
to a new troop today.

261
00:26:46.480 --> 00:26:49.836
I cannot talk about this transfer now.

262
00:26:51.280 --> 00:26:52.998
<i>Take good care of yourself.</i>

263
00:27:06.600 --> 00:27:07.874
Look at this picture.

264
00:27:11.000 --> 00:27:12.638
That's some fancy castle.

265
00:27:13.880 --> 00:27:16.440
You know who this castle was built for?

266
00:27:17.240 --> 00:27:18.958
Someone who was already dead.

267
00:27:20.920 --> 00:27:23.354
They must have had
a lot of money back then. . .

268
00:27:23.840 --> 00:27:25.876
to build a castle like that
for a dead person.

269
00:27:27.440 --> 00:27:29.556
Why are you reading that book anyway?

270
00:27:30.120 --> 00:27:32.714
We're never going to war over there.

271
00:27:33.880 --> 00:27:36.792
We'll be lucky if we even get
a hole in the ground when we're dead.

272
00:27:37.520 --> 00:27:39.431
Don't talk about that. It's bad luck.

273
00:27:44.880 --> 00:27:46.598
Is this the 312th?

274
00:27:46.920 --> 00:27:48.273
That's right.

275
00:27:49.120 --> 00:27:51.588
I'm Nozaki. This is Saigo.

276
00:27:54.120 --> 00:27:56.714
Shimizu. you can put your bedroll there.

277
00:28:01.000 --> 00:28:02.797
There's an empty space in the back.

278
00:28:04.360 --> 00:28:05.554
Don't mind him.

279
00:28:06.760 --> 00:28:10.070
His friend Kashiwara just died.

280
00:28:10.920 --> 00:28:12.638
That used to be his spot.

281
00:28:20.000 --> 00:28:21.831
But we are all going to die.

282
00:28:22.600 --> 00:28:24.511
That's the plan. isn't it?

283
00:28:26.680 --> 00:28:28.591
For our country. it is an honor.

284
00:28:30.800 --> 00:28:32.995
Kashiwara died of honorable dysentery.

285
00:28:34.400 --> 00:28:36.960
Shimizu. where are you from?

286
00:28:39.200 --> 00:28:40.394
Kanagawa-ken.

287
00:28:42.040 --> 00:28:43.996
Ozawa is from there. aren't you?

288
00:28:45.000 --> 00:28:46.274
That's right.

289
00:28:50.080 --> 00:28:51.638
Where were you trained?

290
00:28:52.360 --> 00:28:55.193
Maybe we were at the same school?

291
00:28:56.200 --> 00:28:57.235
No.

292
00:28:57.920 --> 00:28:59.990
I trained in Tokyo.

293
00:29:00.400 --> 00:29:02.630
I trained in Tokyo. too. Where?

294
00:29:09.760 --> 00:29:11.830
<i>The Koho Kimmu Yoin Yoseijo.</i>

295
00:29:23.120 --> 00:29:24.348
Hey. . .

296
00:29:25.760 --> 00:29:27.955
<i>why do you think they put
a Kempeitai in our unit?</i>

297
00:29:28.120 --> 00:29:29.439
I don't know.

298
00:29:33.600 --> 00:29:36.637
<i>He's not wearing the white armband.
He's not Kempeitai.</i>

299
00:29:38.360 --> 00:29:40.430
<i>He went to the Kempeitai
military academy.</i>

300
00:29:41.480 --> 00:29:43.357
Maybe he was kicked out.

301
00:29:46.920 --> 00:29:48.990
<i>He acts like a Kempeitai.</i>

302
00:29:53.400 --> 00:29:55.755
Look at his holster.
That's not standard issue.

303
00:29:57.840 --> 00:30:01.037
He's been put here to spy on us.

304
00:30:02.720 --> 00:30:05.109
Why would he spy on us?

305
00:30:06.880 --> 00:30:10.350
Maybe it's those letters
you've been writing.

306
00:30:12.600 --> 00:30:14.113
You should be careful.

307
00:30:39.680 --> 00:30:41.671
Weed soup again?

308
00:30:43.680 --> 00:30:47.036
Kuribayashi is conserving
our food supplies for the battle.

309
00:30:47.880 --> 00:30:51.475
We'll be dead
before the Americans even get here.

310
00:30:53.240 --> 00:30:56.232
And you would think that with all my
war effort contributions. . .

311
00:30:56.480 --> 00:30:59.916
we should be eating kasutera cakes
or sandwiches.

312
00:31:01.280 --> 00:31:02.395
What?

313
00:31:03.120 --> 00:31:08.148
I ran a bakery in Ohmiya with my wife.

314
00:31:08.560 --> 00:31:10.312
Back when we could still get sugar. . .

315
00:31:11.720 --> 00:31:16.157
we sold ampan and kasutera cakes.

316
00:31:23.720 --> 00:31:27.474
<i>However. his Kempeitai brethren. . .</i>

317
00:31:28.480 --> 00:31:30.755
used to come and take
whatever they wanted.

318
00:31:34.000 --> 00:31:35.638
For the war. . .

319
00:31:37.400 --> 00:31:39.118
For the country. . .

320
00:31:41.480 --> 00:31:42.993
Why bread?

321
00:31:46.040 --> 00:31:51.114
We ran into those types
at our clothing store as well.

322
00:31:53.360 --> 00:31:55.555
When we started making sandwiches. . .

323
00:31:57.000 --> 00:31:59.116
they took those. too.

324
00:32:01.120 --> 00:32:04.556
And when we ran out of meat
and just had bread. they still came.

325
00:32:09.520 --> 00:32:13.672
Eventually. they took all of our
baking equipment for the metal. . .

326
00:32:16.240 --> 00:32:19.232
and we were out of business.

327
00:32:23.000 --> 00:32:24.718
I should have been a fisherman.

328
00:32:27.960 --> 00:32:30.076
It must have been hard on your wife. . .

329
00:32:32.840 --> 00:32:35.274
without the shop
and without her husband.

330
00:33:07.600 --> 00:33:11.388
Tell them to go away.
We have nothing to sell.

331
00:33:17.200 --> 00:33:20.795
Congratulations! Your husband
is going to war.

332
00:33:34.920 --> 00:33:36.638
Thank you very much.

333
00:33:37.280 --> 00:33:40.955
I'm happy to serve the country.

334
00:33:44.880 --> 00:33:48.236
Prayers for your eternal success at arms.

335
00:33:48.800 --> 00:33:53.078
I beg of you! We have only each other.

336
00:33:56.640 --> 00:33:59.029
This is not the time.

337
00:34:01.000 --> 00:34:05.471
We have all sent our husbands
and sons to war.

338
00:34:06.280 --> 00:34:10.319
We all have to do our part.

339
00:34:14.000 --> 00:34:16.673
At least you'll have a little one
to carry on your name.

340
00:34:29.440 --> 00:34:31.874
I can't eat with you like that.

341
00:34:34.760 --> 00:34:38.878
What am I going to do after you die?

342
00:34:45.000 --> 00:34:47.150
I'm not in the coffin yet.

343
00:34:49.840 --> 00:34:53.435
The men never come home.
not even a soul.

344
00:34:56.120 --> 00:34:57.917
They'll never let you come home.

345
00:34:59.880 --> 00:35:01.233
Don't worry.

346
00:35:03.640 --> 00:35:05.198
And now. with the baby.

347
00:35:27.920 --> 00:35:29.148
Can you hear me?

348
00:35:30.840 --> 00:35:32.068
It's Dad.

349
00:35:34.920 --> 00:35:35.955
Listen.

350
00:35:38.800 --> 00:35:42.349
Don't tell anyone
what I'm telling you now.

351
00:35:44.560 --> 00:35:45.675
It's a secret.

352
00:36:00.280 --> 00:36:01.429
Your dad. . .

353
00:36:05.120 --> 00:36:07.076
is going to come home for you.

354
00:37:01.040 --> 00:37:02.189
Hurry up!

355
00:37:05.480 --> 00:37:06.959
The enemy approaches!

356
00:37:17.240 --> 00:37:18.559
This is ridiculous!

357
00:37:19.120 --> 00:37:21.315
Why waste time digging these tunnels?

358
00:37:21.960 --> 00:37:23.951
They are all going to die anyway.

359
00:37:24.520 --> 00:37:27.956
At least he conceded
to the pillboxes on the beach.

360
00:37:40.360 --> 00:37:41.998
You wanted to see me. sir?

361
00:37:43.120 --> 00:37:44.599
Care for a drink?

362
00:37:49.840 --> 00:37:52.035
You have been looking
quite pale these days.

363
00:37:55.400 --> 00:37:59.075
It's the water. It has
never agreed with me.

364
00:37:59.480 --> 00:38:00.629
That's not good.

365
00:38:02.120 --> 00:38:05.032
Why don't you go back
to the mainland to recoup?

366
00:38:06.560 --> 00:38:10.553
I have commissioned Admiral Ichimaru
to take your place.

367
00:38:12.200 --> 00:38:14.395
We are wasting time
digging these tunnels.

368
00:38:15.080 --> 00:38:19.039
General. the island won't last
five days without fleet support.

369
00:38:20.560 --> 00:38:22.835
We should fight to the death.

370
00:38:24.200 --> 00:38:28.352
The tunnel-digging may be futile.

371
00:38:29.120 --> 00:38:32.874
Maybe the stand on Iwo will be futile.

372
00:38:33.320 --> 00:38:35.436
Maybe the whole war is futile.

373
00:38:35.600 --> 00:38:37.192
But will you give up then?

374
00:38:37.520 --> 00:38:39.556
We will defend this island
until we are dead!

375
00:38:39.720 --> 00:38:41.870
Until the very last soldier is dead!

376
00:38:42.680 --> 00:38:46.832
If our children can live safely
for one more day. . .

377
00:38:47.080 --> 00:38:50.072
it would be worth the one more day
that we defend this island!

378
00:38:50.960 --> 00:38:52.109
Ohsugi. . .

379
00:38:52.680 --> 00:38:56.514
if you have an ounce
of pride left as an officer. . .

380
00:38:57.360 --> 00:38:58.634
I beg of you. . .

381
00:38:59.240 --> 00:39:02.232
go back to headquarters
and ask them to send support.

382
00:39:25.960 --> 00:39:29.509
So the rumor is true?
I couldn't believe it.

383
00:39:30.880 --> 00:39:34.555
I'm grateful to be leaving this island.

384
00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:38.151
We may have had our differences. . .

385
00:39:39.280 --> 00:39:42.033
but I'm truly sorry to see you go.

386
00:39:43.480 --> 00:39:46.517
General Hayashi. it is up to you now.

387
00:39:48.040 --> 00:39:52.716
Kuribayashi belongs behind a desk.
not commanding war.

388
00:39:53.440 --> 00:39:54.759
I understand.

389
00:39:55.080 --> 00:39:58.470
There are many of us
who agree with you. sir.

390
00:40:12.920 --> 00:40:13.909
Listen.

391
00:40:14.400 --> 00:40:17.949
The Americans are likely to land here.

392
00:40:19.400 --> 00:40:21.709
Crossfire positions will be here. . .

393
00:40:22.800 --> 00:40:23.789
here. . .

394
00:40:24.880 --> 00:40:25.995
and here.

395
00:40:27.360 --> 00:40:28.588
The fact is. . .

396
00:40:28.760 --> 00:40:34.790
we are completely
outnumbered in every sector.

397
00:40:36.520 --> 00:40:38.431
But we have a great advantage.

398
00:40:39.400 --> 00:40:41.868
Can anyone tell me what that is?

399
00:40:47.240 --> 00:40:50.118
The Americans are weak-willed
and inferior to Japanese soldiers.

400
00:40:50.280 --> 00:40:51.679
Very good. Shimizu.

401
00:40:52.560 --> 00:40:53.993
Why is that?

402
00:40:54.280 --> 00:40:55.793
They are not as disciplined. . .

403
00:40:55.960 --> 00:40:58.554
and they let their emotions
interfere with their duty.

404
00:40:58.720 --> 00:40:59.948
That is correct.

405
00:41:03.480 --> 00:41:06.358
Here is the uniform
of an American medic.

406
00:41:07.760 --> 00:41:08.954
He should be your target.

407
00:41:09.760 --> 00:41:13.673
For Americans will risk the lives
of many soldiers to save this one.

408
00:41:14.560 --> 00:41:15.595
Understood?

409
00:41:26.680 --> 00:41:29.478
General. may I speak with you?

410
00:41:31.800 --> 00:41:34.109
Please keep an eye on
Major General Hayashi.

411
00:41:36.280 --> 00:41:38.396
Thank you for your concern. Nishi. . .

412
00:41:38.720 --> 00:41:41.632
but we don't have any time to waste.

413
00:41:41.960 --> 00:41:45.077
We must think about what
we can do at this moment.

414
00:41:48.240 --> 00:41:49.639
Admiral Ichimaru.

415
00:41:52.680 --> 00:41:54.477
Reporting for duty. sir.

416
00:41:55.440 --> 00:41:56.998
Excuse me.

417
00:41:57.400 --> 00:41:59.868
Thank you for coming
on such short notice.

418
00:43:53.480 --> 00:43:54.595
Jupiter!

419
00:43:57.320 --> 00:43:58.548
Jupiter.

420
00:44:47.720 --> 00:44:48.869
Yamazaki. . .

421
00:44:49.880 --> 00:44:52.872
what are you doing just
sitting there? Help us--

422
00:45:31.200 --> 00:45:33.919
I think he's writing about us
in his reports.

423
00:45:35.080 --> 00:45:36.672
He's just writing a letter.

424
00:45:37.160 --> 00:45:39.913
It's been two months. Nozaki.

425
00:45:41.320 --> 00:45:43.038
He would have reported us by now.

426
00:45:43.200 --> 00:45:44.872
How can you be sure?

427
00:45:52.560 --> 00:45:55.233
Will they ever stop?

428
00:45:55.680 --> 00:45:58.592
Day and night. day and night. . .

429
00:46:00.880 --> 00:46:02.757
It's driving me crazy!

430
00:46:03.560 --> 00:46:07.758
If the damn Americans
are going to invade. . .

431
00:46:09.560 --> 00:46:11.437
why don't they hurry up and land?

432
00:46:25.520 --> 00:46:26.748
<i>Tako-Chan...</i>

433
00:46:27.080 --> 00:46:30.914
the four chicks that were born
two months ago have grown so much.

434
00:46:31.360 --> 00:46:35.239
<i>The mother chicken leads them
for food every day...</i>

435
00:46:35.720 --> 00:46:39.713
but they're giving me a hard time. picking
at the vegetable garden I have grown.

436
00:46:44.480 --> 00:46:47.677
The fleet of American ships
has left Saipan.

437
00:46:55.760 --> 00:46:57.352
So they are on their way.

438
00:46:58.920 --> 00:47:00.638
Ready the troops.

439
00:47:34.920 --> 00:47:36.035
Men. . .

440
00:47:37.320 --> 00:47:40.198
the time has come
to show your true colors.

441
00:47:41.120 --> 00:47:43.350
As a member of the honorable
lmperial Army. . .

442
00:47:44.080 --> 00:47:46.435
I trust that you will fight with honor.

443
00:47:49.560 --> 00:47:53.348
This island is of utmost importance
to Japan.

444
00:47:54.600 --> 00:47:55.919
<i>Should the island fall...</i>

445
00:47:58.120 --> 00:47:59.712
the enemy. . .

446
00:48:00.600 --> 00:48:04.513
will use it as their base
to attack our homeland.

447
00:48:05.880 --> 00:48:07.393
For the mainland. . .

448
00:48:08.800 --> 00:48:10.313
For our homeland. . .

449
00:48:10.840 --> 00:48:13.149
Until the very last man.

450
00:48:14.000 --> 00:48:17.037
<i>Our duty is to stop the enemy right here.</i>

451
00:48:18.400 --> 00:48:19.799
<i>Not one of you...</i>

452
00:48:20.400 --> 00:48:23.472
is allowed to die until you have killed
10 enemy soldiers.

453
00:48:27.360 --> 00:48:30.557
Do not expect to return home alive.

454
00:48:33.240 --> 00:48:36.915
I will always be in front of you.

455
00:48:45.680 --> 00:48:47.272
Long live the Emperor.

456
00:49:29.560 --> 00:49:32.757
<i>Take care and be well.</i>

457
00:49:34.200 --> 00:49:39.115
<i>I will fight courageously until the end.
in the spirit of Yamato.</i>

458
00:49:40.240 --> 00:49:44.438
My heart will always be with you.

459
00:49:45.440 --> 00:49:46.634
<i>Takeichi.</i>

460
00:50:02.360 --> 00:50:07.514
<i>Every household is assigned a quota
of bag-making for the gunpowder.</i>

461
00:50:08.280 --> 00:50:12.592
I cannot help but get tense when I think
that these will be used in battle.

462
00:50:13.400 --> 00:50:16.278
<i>Taro and Yoko laugh at me for this.</i>

463
00:50:17.120 --> 00:50:20.317
<i>Takako. on evacuation in Nagano.
is also doing well.</i>

464
00:50:21.120 --> 00:50:23.156
I pray for your safety.

465
00:50:24.120 --> 00:50:26.395
<i>Sincerely. Yoshi.</i>

466
00:50:39.760 --> 00:50:41.398
No one can shoot me now.

467
00:50:45.240 --> 00:50:49.279
That's a nice belt.
My wife sent me one. too.

468
00:50:53.840 --> 00:50:57.833
<i>Doesn't look like Mr. Kempeitai
has a thousand-stitch belt. does he?</i>

469
00:50:58.200 --> 00:51:00.589
Maybe he thinks it will clash
with his uniform.

470
00:51:00.760 --> 00:51:03.194
He probably doesn't believe
in superstitions. anyway.

471
00:51:07.960 --> 00:51:10.155
His mother made him one after all.

472
00:51:32.320 --> 00:51:35.357
- Maybe they're trying to sink the island.
- My head hurts.

473
00:51:35.600 --> 00:51:38.478
How many ships do you think
there are out there?

474
00:51:38.640 --> 00:51:42.189
At least 30. Maybe even 50.

475
00:51:42.520 --> 00:51:44.988
- They must be really close.
- I need to take a leak.

476
00:51:45.160 --> 00:51:47.799
Don't go near the sewers.
Dysentery is spreading through there.

477
00:51:47.960 --> 00:51:49.075
Where do I go then?

478
00:51:49.400 --> 00:51:51.311
There is a pot at the end of the cave.

479
00:52:10.840 --> 00:52:12.637
The shit pot is full.

480
00:52:12.920 --> 00:52:14.797
Someone needs to throw it out.

481
00:52:37.400 --> 00:52:39.675
If anything happens to that pot. . .

482
00:52:41.080 --> 00:52:45.756
you'll be carrying our shit away
with your hands.

483
00:53:50.080 --> 00:53:51.832
Is this some kind of a joke?

484
00:53:52.800 --> 00:53:55.189
Why are you always picking on me?

485
00:54:32.560 --> 00:54:36.838
Thank you. God. I take back
what I said before.

486
00:54:50.960 --> 00:54:52.712
Shall we commence fire?

487
00:54:53.080 --> 00:54:54.115
Not yet.

488
00:54:59.040 --> 00:55:01.508
The men wish to commence firing.

489
00:55:08.720 --> 00:55:09.994
Hold your fire!

490
00:55:13.200 --> 00:55:14.474
Hold your fire!

491
00:55:14.800 --> 00:55:16.074
Hold your fire!

492
00:55:23.800 --> 00:55:26.712
They will take the beach
in no time if we do not resist.

493
00:55:26.880 --> 00:55:28.791
Wait until the beach is full.

494
00:55:50.560 --> 00:55:53.313
Let's go. Commence firing!

495
00:55:59.040 --> 00:56:00.393
Commence firing!

496
00:56:01.480 --> 00:56:02.879
<i>Commence firing!</i>

497
00:57:02.440 --> 00:57:04.396
The guns of the Kitakubo unit
were destroyed.

498
00:57:04.560 --> 00:57:06.790
All the pillbox units on the beach
have been destroyed.

499
00:57:06.960 --> 00:57:08.791
However. all other forces are intact. . .

500
00:57:08.960 --> 00:57:11.110
and we estimate more than
1.000 enemy casualties.

501
00:57:11.600 --> 00:57:13.909
The pillbox destruction was unavoidable.

502
00:57:14.280 --> 00:57:16.316
Overall. that is good news.

503
00:57:16.560 --> 00:57:18.391
How are the men
holding up at Suribachi?

504
00:57:19.440 --> 00:57:20.759
Forces are intact.

505
00:57:24.360 --> 00:57:25.713
What is the enemy situation?

506
00:57:25.880 --> 00:57:28.758
Approximately 20.000 men and 80 tanks.

507
00:57:29.120 --> 00:57:33.193
There has to be more than that.
They still have men waiting in the boats.

508
00:57:33.400 --> 00:57:35.789
Currently the enemy front extends. . .

509
00:57:36.240 --> 00:57:38.834
between Suribachi
and the south landing. . .

510
00:57:39.360 --> 00:57:41.510
and Chidori airfield south.

511
00:57:42.160 --> 00:57:46.199
Just as I thought. . . Suribachi
and the Motoyama airfield.

512
00:57:47.120 --> 00:57:49.315
They are making a two-pronged attack.

513
00:58:04.040 --> 00:58:07.077
That's not enough! I need more ammo.

514
00:58:31.280 --> 00:58:32.554
Take his place!

515
00:58:32.960 --> 00:58:34.996
- The machine gun is blasted.
- Use your rifle!

516
00:58:37.480 --> 00:58:38.959
Watch out! lmbecile!

517
00:58:40.000 --> 00:58:41.149
I can't rely on you.

518
00:58:41.320 --> 00:58:44.392
Go send a report to Colonel Adachi
that we need another machine gun.

519
00:58:44.800 --> 00:58:45.994
Hurry up!

520
00:59:11.360 --> 00:59:13.510
Colonel Adachi is asking
for reinforcements.

521
00:59:13.880 --> 00:59:17.998
We can't afford to send reinforcements.
Tell him to hold out.

522
00:59:28.920 --> 00:59:30.148
Shoot him!

523
00:59:37.840 --> 00:59:40.070
- What's the matter?
- We're out of bullets!

524
00:59:58.000 --> 00:59:59.911
We are losing Suribachi.

525
01:00:00.720 --> 01:00:04.872
All is lost. Request permission
to lead a suicide mission.

526
01:00:05.360 --> 01:00:08.238
No. You must try to hold them off.

527
01:00:08.960 --> 01:00:12.635
Do what you can to survive
and join forces in the north caves.

528
01:00:13.400 --> 01:00:14.435
But. sir. . .

529
01:00:15.120 --> 01:00:17.918
I have failed to hold Suribachi.

530
01:00:18.160 --> 01:00:20.958
Permit me to die with honor with
my men.

531
01:00:21.280 --> 01:00:22.395
No. Colonel.

532
01:00:23.040 --> 01:00:24.314
<i>This is an order!</i>

533
01:00:29.520 --> 01:00:30.635
Adachi.

534
01:00:32.720 --> 01:00:33.835
Adachi!

535
01:00:46.240 --> 01:00:50.074
Sir. Captain Tanida
requests machine guns.

536
01:00:52.160 --> 01:00:53.388
It's over.

537
01:01:01.200 --> 01:01:02.349
Suicide. . .

538
01:01:03.680 --> 01:01:05.557
That's the only thing left.

539
01:01:06.400 --> 01:01:07.389
But--

540
01:01:08.680 --> 01:01:11.558
Here. take this to your commander.

541
01:01:54.680 --> 01:01:58.150
I heard General Kuribayashi
order Colonel Adachi to escape.

542
01:01:58.320 --> 01:01:59.309
Quiet!

543
01:02:02.720 --> 01:02:05.837
Escape is the coward's way.

544
01:02:06.960 --> 01:02:08.154
Sit down!

545
01:02:19.800 --> 01:02:20.835
Men. . .

546
01:02:23.600 --> 01:02:24.635
we are. . .

547
01:02:27.360 --> 01:02:29.590
honorable soldiers of the Emperor.

548
01:02:33.160 --> 01:02:34.639
Don't ever forget that.

549
01:02:38.640 --> 01:02:40.471
The only way left for us. . .

550
01:02:42.320 --> 01:02:44.151
is to die with honor.

551
01:02:47.760 --> 01:02:49.193
This is our fate. . .

552
01:02:50.800 --> 01:02:53.030
to find our place at Yasukuni Shrine.

553
01:02:57.920 --> 01:02:59.512
I'll see you there.

554
01:03:18.480 --> 01:03:20.391
Soldiers. farewell!

555
01:05:10.960 --> 01:05:11.995
Stop!

556
01:05:19.280 --> 01:05:22.716
You should die like an honorable soldier.

557
01:05:23.560 --> 01:05:25.039
Look. Shimizu. . .

558
01:05:27.680 --> 01:05:30.353
we can still join the troops
in the northern caves.

559
01:05:31.280 --> 01:05:33.840
Our orders are to stay here until death.

560
01:05:34.000 --> 01:05:35.752
I heard General Kuribayashi himself.

561
01:05:36.840 --> 01:05:38.432
That's what he said. . .

562
01:05:40.200 --> 01:05:41.474
over the radio.

563
01:05:42.880 --> 01:05:44.074
It's true.

564
01:05:48.080 --> 01:05:50.150
We can die here. . .

565
01:05:51.720 --> 01:05:54.154
or we can continue fighting.

566
01:05:57.440 --> 01:06:00.193
Which would better serve the Emperor?

567
01:06:02.960 --> 01:06:04.393
Which one?

568
01:06:25.680 --> 01:06:26.999
Where does this go?

569
01:06:27.160 --> 01:06:29.355
It will take us closer to Motoyama.

570
01:06:35.200 --> 01:06:36.952
Do you have orders to move back?

571
01:06:38.320 --> 01:06:40.197
Where are the rest of your men?

572
01:06:40.680 --> 01:06:41.954
All dead.

573
01:06:43.440 --> 01:06:45.237
It's the same with us.

574
01:06:52.920 --> 01:06:55.070
There should be an outlet
somewhere near here.

575
01:06:55.280 --> 01:06:56.395
Be quiet!

576
01:07:42.160 --> 01:07:46.790
So you thought you could blow us up.
or burn us alive. did you?

577
01:08:01.840 --> 01:08:04.070
- Have we heard from Suribachi?
- No. sir.

578
01:08:04.240 --> 01:08:05.719
Send a messenger!

579
01:08:13.400 --> 01:08:17.188
Lieutenant Oiso has ordered us
to rendezvous at the east cave.

580
01:08:25.040 --> 01:08:27.873
We will make a run for Motoyama.

581
01:08:28.560 --> 01:08:31.074
There is no cover for two kilometers.

582
01:08:31.800 --> 01:08:34.314
It will be every man for himself.

583
01:08:40.720 --> 01:08:42.472
See you on the other side.

584
01:08:43.120 --> 01:08:46.749
If not on this earth.
then in the next world.

585
01:09:01.120 --> 01:09:03.680
Don't run with the herd.
That's where the enemy will fire.

586
01:09:03.840 --> 01:09:04.989
Stay back.

587
01:09:05.760 --> 01:09:07.079
That's cowardice!

588
01:09:08.960 --> 01:09:12.316
There is no use for a dead soldier.

589
01:09:41.040 --> 01:09:43.110
Wait until the flare is gone.

590
01:10:08.160 --> 01:10:09.832
Crawl forward.

591
01:10:27.560 --> 01:10:29.039
What happened to the messenger?

592
01:10:29.280 --> 01:10:30.599
He never came back.

593
01:10:34.440 --> 01:10:35.998
I will go to Adachi myself.

594
01:10:36.240 --> 01:10:39.232
Motoyama's transmitter
still works. General.

595
01:10:40.440 --> 01:10:42.237
Why not try there. sir?

596
01:11:02.480 --> 01:11:04.391
Sir. these men retreated
from Mt. Suribachi.

597
01:11:11.200 --> 01:11:12.519
What are your names?

598
01:11:12.800 --> 01:11:15.234
Saigo. from the 312th.

599
01:11:15.840 --> 01:11:17.319
Shimizu. reporting for duty.

600
01:11:19.400 --> 01:11:21.311
You escaped from Suribachi?

601
01:11:27.520 --> 01:11:29.476
How dare you!

602
01:11:31.320 --> 01:11:34.118
It was your duty
to stay in your position until death.

603
01:11:36.320 --> 01:11:37.833
You should have died. . .

604
01:11:38.720 --> 01:11:40.995
with your fellow troop members.

605
01:11:42.160 --> 01:11:45.835
You are both a disgrace.

606
01:11:49.800 --> 01:11:51.233
Get on your knees.

607
01:11:53.760 --> 01:11:56.354
- But. sir--
- I said. get on your knees!

608
01:12:15.760 --> 01:12:18.069
I don't want you to kill
my soldiers needlessly.

609
01:12:19.720 --> 01:12:21.233
Put down your sword.

610
01:12:21.720 --> 01:12:22.994
Put it down!

611
01:12:29.120 --> 01:12:30.599
What's going on here?

612
01:12:32.840 --> 01:12:36.879
These men ran from Suribachi.

613
01:12:39.280 --> 01:12:43.910
Lt. Ito. I gave the order that all survivors
retreat to the north caves.

614
01:12:46.160 --> 01:12:47.752
I am very sorry. General.

615
01:12:49.920 --> 01:12:51.114
It's just. . .

616
01:12:52.360 --> 01:12:53.759
Suribachi. . .

617
01:12:56.040 --> 01:12:57.393
has fallen.

618
01:13:17.840 --> 01:13:19.432
Now that Suribachi has been taken. . .

619
01:13:19.600 --> 01:13:21.909
the enemy will maneuver all forces
onto the hillside.

620
01:13:22.080 --> 01:13:23.991
We must move
our command center north. sir.

621
01:13:30.120 --> 01:13:31.189
Ito. . .

622
01:13:33.280 --> 01:13:35.350
fight for your fallen brethren. . .

623
01:13:37.120 --> 01:13:38.758
until the end.

624
01:14:00.360 --> 01:14:01.759
Get up!

625
01:14:05.880 --> 01:14:07.836
Major General Hayashi
is leading an attack.

626
01:14:08.000 --> 01:14:09.558
We are to join him.

627
01:14:12.960 --> 01:14:15.235
Kuribayashi's orders are
to remain in the caves.

628
01:14:17.640 --> 01:14:21.758
Lieutenant lto says Kuribayashi
is a weak American sympathizer.

629
01:14:31.280 --> 01:14:33.999
We will take back Mt. Suribachi.

630
01:14:55.200 --> 01:14:57.156
Where is Major General Hayashi?

631
01:14:59.640 --> 01:15:00.959
We don't know. sir.

632
01:15:01.560 --> 01:15:02.913
Who is in charge here?

633
01:15:03.160 --> 01:15:04.957
I'm not sure.

634
01:15:08.000 --> 01:15:10.230
Stay here until
I determine the plan of action.

635
01:15:34.960 --> 01:15:36.393
We're dead.

636
01:15:42.120 --> 01:15:44.156
Pull back!

637
01:15:44.680 --> 01:15:46.432
We'll get reinforcements.

638
01:16:17.440 --> 01:16:22.070
Why didn't your regiment join the attack?

639
01:16:25.960 --> 01:16:27.598
Don't sit here like rats!

640
01:16:28.440 --> 01:16:31.876
Come out of your caves and fight!

641
01:16:33.600 --> 01:16:35.113
Where is your commander?

642
01:16:35.280 --> 01:16:37.077
We haven't received the order to attack.

643
01:16:40.600 --> 01:16:43.239
Didn't you receive the order
from General Hayashi?

644
01:16:44.600 --> 01:16:47.558
Kuribayashi countermanded
Hayashi's order.

645
01:16:48.080 --> 01:16:49.911
There is to be no attack.

646
01:16:53.440 --> 01:16:55.510
We will take back Suribachi. . .

647
01:16:56.440 --> 01:16:57.998
with or without Kuribayashi.

648
01:16:58.680 --> 01:17:01.752
There are already troops on the attack.
Get your men in order.

649
01:17:01.920 --> 01:17:04.480
Lieutenant. may I remind you
of your rank!

650
01:17:04.640 --> 01:17:06.915
Your disrespect for senior officers. . .

651
01:17:07.720 --> 01:17:10.393
puts your men at needless risk.

652
01:17:12.360 --> 01:17:14.271
I suggest you go back to your cave. . .

653
01:17:14.440 --> 01:17:18.149
or hand over your men.

654
01:17:27.960 --> 01:17:29.109
Enough.

655
01:17:29.520 --> 01:17:31.192
We'll do it ourselves.

656
01:17:41.840 --> 01:17:43.159
That's against regulations.

657
01:17:43.480 --> 01:17:46.916
That's the officer who tried to kill us.
He doesn't care.

658
01:18:17.760 --> 01:18:19.079
I won't go back.

659
01:18:21.040 --> 01:18:23.156
I've had enough of cave fighting.

660
01:18:25.280 --> 01:18:28.033
You men are now under
Lieutenant Colonel Nishi's command.

661
01:18:39.640 --> 01:18:41.437
I will throw myself under an enemy tank.

662
01:18:44.880 --> 01:18:47.314
I will take out one of their machines.

663
01:19:14.760 --> 01:19:15.954
Hurry.

664
01:19:18.240 --> 01:19:19.593
What is the status?

665
01:19:21.320 --> 01:19:22.992
A thousand men were lost. . .

666
01:19:23.160 --> 01:19:24.957
in a night attack along Chidori airfield.

667
01:19:25.120 --> 01:19:27.793
Why? I have given them strict orders
not to kill themselves.

668
01:19:27.960 --> 01:19:31.555
It seems that the order to retreat
was not conveyed to all sectors.

669
01:19:32.400 --> 01:19:33.594
Hayashi.

670
01:19:34.080 --> 01:19:35.354
Damn you!

671
01:19:36.400 --> 01:19:37.833
And the American advancement?

672
01:19:38.400 --> 01:19:42.029
A battalion is headed north and we
are fighting back along the west ridge.

673
01:19:42.200 --> 01:19:46.273
Good. Once they cross the west ridge.
they will be surrounded on three sides.

674
01:19:47.640 --> 01:19:48.868
This just arrived.

675
01:19:49.040 --> 01:19:50.109
Read it.

676
01:19:54.880 --> 01:19:56.359
From headquarters. . .

677
01:19:58.440 --> 01:20:02.911
" We regret that we are unable to send
reinforcements to Iwo at this time.

678
01:20:04.280 --> 01:20:07.636
We earnestly hope you will
fight honorably. . .

679
01:20:08.360 --> 01:20:10.476
and die for your country. "

680
01:21:48.360 --> 01:21:49.429
Bring him in.

681
01:22:04.560 --> 01:22:05.549
Bring him in.

682
01:22:15.560 --> 01:22:17.630
Shall I finish him off?

683
01:22:18.360 --> 01:22:20.271
No. Treat him.

684
01:22:21.640 --> 01:22:22.834
But. sir--

685
01:22:23.000 --> 01:22:25.514
Okubo. you would expect the same.
wouldn't you?

686
01:22:25.680 --> 01:22:26.908
Endo. treat him.

687
01:22:27.320 --> 01:22:29.993
We are low on morphine as it is.

688
01:22:31.400 --> 01:22:34.119
Sir. the Americans would not treat
a wounded Japanese soldier.

689
01:22:34.280 --> 01:22:37.113
Son. have you ever met one?

690
01:22:38.600 --> 01:22:39.669
Treat him.

691
01:23:15.640 --> 01:23:17.631
Where are you. American tanks?

692
01:23:18.680 --> 01:23:20.238
Come and get me!

693
01:23:35.240 --> 01:23:36.798
How is the prisoner doing?

694
01:23:37.280 --> 01:23:38.554
He is awake. sir.

695
01:23:42.360 --> 01:23:45.397
I will question the prisoner
for information.

696
01:25:27.560 --> 01:25:28.754
Damn.

697
01:25:31.040 --> 01:25:32.473
I've had enough of this.

698
01:25:33.160 --> 01:25:34.673
I'm going to surrender.

699
01:25:39.200 --> 01:25:41.031
Go ahead and arrest me.

700
01:25:42.240 --> 01:25:45.835
I don't care anymore. That's what
you were put here for. isn't it?

701
01:25:47.200 --> 01:25:49.555
To report treasonous thoughts.

702
01:25:53.880 --> 01:25:55.598
I was put here because. . .

703
01:25:57.000 --> 01:25:59.036
<i>I was discharged from the Kempeitai.</i>

704
01:26:02.160 --> 01:26:03.275
Discharged?

705
01:26:07.720 --> 01:26:10.871
I had only been in service
for five days.

706
01:26:14.000 --> 01:26:15.035
Shimizu. . .

707
01:26:15.200 --> 01:26:17.839
you must always be firm.

708
01:26:18.920 --> 01:26:22.959
Any mercy and people
will take advantage of you.

709
01:26:28.240 --> 01:26:29.355
That's unpatriotic.

710
01:26:29.640 --> 01:26:31.119
Go sort it out. Shimizu.

711
01:26:43.280 --> 01:26:45.999
You do not have the lmperial flag
properly displayed.

712
01:26:46.160 --> 01:26:47.354
I'm sorry.

713
01:26:47.520 --> 01:26:50.876
My husband has gone to war
and I couldn't put it up myself.

714
01:26:51.040 --> 01:26:53.634
It is unpatriotic
not to have the flag displayed.

715
01:26:53.800 --> 01:26:55.995
If you help me. I'll put it up now.

716
01:27:15.680 --> 01:27:17.511
Get that dog to shut up.

717
01:27:19.040 --> 01:27:20.155
What was that. sir?

718
01:27:21.280 --> 01:27:25.353
That dog is a nuisance.
It is disruptive of Army communications.

719
01:27:25.920 --> 01:27:27.876
I am very sorry. sir.

720
01:27:34.000 --> 01:27:35.991
Shimizu. Dispose of the dog.

721
01:27:37.280 --> 01:27:40.670
We can't have a dog interfering
with important military commands.

722
01:27:46.240 --> 01:27:47.798
Take the dog in the back.

723
01:27:48.120 --> 01:27:49.439
It's only a dog.

724
01:27:49.640 --> 01:27:52.108
It won't happen again.

725
01:27:52.560 --> 01:27:53.913
Take it out back.

726
01:27:54.400 --> 01:27:55.992
Keep the children inside.

727
01:27:57.120 --> 01:27:58.314
Hurry up.

728
01:28:44.640 --> 01:28:46.870
Take the dog into the house
and keep him quiet. . .

729
01:28:47.520 --> 01:28:48.509
and never let him out.

730
01:29:00.200 --> 01:29:01.679
It's taken care of. sir.

731
01:29:38.480 --> 01:29:40.311
Are you trying to make a fool out of me?

732
01:29:42.080 --> 01:29:47.200
If you can't even shoot a dog.
you'll never be able to handle the Reds.

733
01:29:48.880 --> 01:29:50.233
You are unpatriotic!

734
01:29:56.200 --> 01:29:58.475
I was discharged for insubordination. . .

735
01:29:59.640 --> 01:30:01.278
and sent here.

736
01:30:09.720 --> 01:30:11.392
Don't look so glum. Shimizu.

737
01:30:12.880 --> 01:30:15.394
At least now only the enemy hates you.

738
01:30:20.320 --> 01:30:21.992
I don't blame the dog.

739
01:30:46.720 --> 01:30:47.835
<i>Taro...</i>

740
01:30:48.240 --> 01:30:51.038
tonight I attended my farewell party.

741
01:30:51.640 --> 01:30:54.074
<i>The wives also attended.
so there was a lot of fuss.</i>

742
01:30:54.240 --> 01:30:57.038
<i>Greeting all the ladies...</i>

743
01:30:57.280 --> 01:31:00.272
<i>kept me from enjoying the food.</i>

744
01:33:38.600 --> 01:33:40.556
Is there any information
of the enemy's plan?

745
01:33:41.320 --> 01:33:43.436
No. it's just a letter.

746
01:33:45.240 --> 01:33:46.958
It's from his mother.

747
01:33:49.320 --> 01:33:50.355
" Sam. . .

748
01:33:51.360 --> 01:33:53.590
I have mailed you
a couple of books to read.

749
01:33:54.200 --> 01:33:55.679
I hope that you like them.

750
01:33:56.960 --> 01:33:57.949
Yesterday. . .

751
01:33:58.680 --> 01:34:03.231
the dogs dug a hole under the fence.

752
01:34:04.560 --> 01:34:08.633
They ran all over the neighborhood.

753
01:34:09.680 --> 01:34:11.796
By the time we found them. . .

754
01:34:12.960 --> 01:34:17.750
the Harrisons' roosters were terrorized.

755
01:34:18.520 --> 01:34:21.239
Don't worry about us.

756
01:34:22.440 --> 01:34:26.353
Just take care of yourself
and come back safely.

757
01:34:26.720 --> 01:34:30.269
Remember what I said to you. . .

758
01:34:33.760 --> 01:34:35.318
always do what is right. . .

759
01:34:36.360 --> 01:34:38.476
because it is right.

760
01:34:39.600 --> 01:34:43.115
I pray for a speedy end to the war. . .

761
01:34:43.280 --> 01:34:44.633
and your safe return.

762
01:34:46.160 --> 01:34:47.434
Love. Mom. "

763
01:35:20.680 --> 01:35:23.194
I'm sorry. sir. There is no more medicine.

764
01:35:23.360 --> 01:35:26.397
It's all right. I'm useless now.
Go help the others!

765
01:36:54.000 --> 01:36:55.956
Okubo. come here.

766
01:37:02.400 --> 01:37:04.072
How are we on ammunition?

767
01:37:06.080 --> 01:37:08.389
Not good. sir.

768
01:37:09.880 --> 01:37:11.757
Our mortars have been taken out. . .

769
01:37:12.520 --> 01:37:14.317
and we're out of machine gun ammo.

770
01:37:16.040 --> 01:37:19.237
We have only our rifles.

771
01:37:21.200 --> 01:37:22.189
Okubo. . .

772
01:37:22.360 --> 01:37:25.989
you are now in charge of the men.

773
01:37:30.560 --> 01:37:32.073
We can no longer hold this area.

774
01:37:32.800 --> 01:37:36.156
You must guide
the rest of the men north.

775
01:37:38.720 --> 01:37:41.951
Take whatever food and ammo
we have left.

776
01:37:43.080 --> 01:37:45.355
What about you. sir?

777
01:37:48.640 --> 01:37:51.916
I'm tired of sharing this cave
with all of you.

778
01:37:52.720 --> 01:37:55.154
I'm a one-man show from here on out.

779
01:37:55.480 --> 01:37:57.152
What are you talking about. sir?

780
01:37:58.480 --> 01:38:01.631
Your first order of business. . .

781
01:38:02.640 --> 01:38:04.312
is to find some water.

782
01:38:30.200 --> 01:38:31.315
Men. . .

783
01:38:32.720 --> 01:38:34.278
do your best.

784
01:38:35.720 --> 01:38:39.952
Do what is right. . .

785
01:38:41.720 --> 01:38:43.870
because it is right.

786
01:38:45.960 --> 01:38:47.154
Understood?

787
01:38:54.640 --> 01:38:59.395
I will make sure that they send you
medicine and food.

788
01:39:01.560 --> 01:39:02.834
It has been a great honor. . .

789
01:39:04.200 --> 01:39:05.394
to serve. . .

790
01:39:06.640 --> 01:39:08.039
under you.

791
01:39:45.600 --> 01:39:47.079
Hand me my rifle.

792
01:40:09.920 --> 01:40:11.717
I'm sorry. Okubo.

793
01:41:28.560 --> 01:41:31.632
Why am I not getting any reports?
Have we heard from Admiral Ichimaru?

794
01:41:31.800 --> 01:41:34.439
- No. sir.
- What about Nishi or Hayashi?

795
01:41:36.800 --> 01:41:39.712
- Send out messengers!
- We have. Many times.

796
01:41:39.960 --> 01:41:41.598
None of them have come back.

797
01:41:42.080 --> 01:41:43.798
You can't plan strategy like this!

798
01:41:54.520 --> 01:41:57.876
I have been thinking about
what Lt. Colonel Nishi said.

799
01:41:58.600 --> 01:41:59.953
He's right.

800
01:42:05.000 --> 01:42:07.798
I don't know anything about the enemy.

801
01:42:08.520 --> 01:42:12.035
I believed that the Americans
were cowards. . .

802
01:42:17.920 --> 01:42:19.638
but they weren't.

803
01:42:24.640 --> 01:42:26.710
I was taught. . .

804
01:42:28.320 --> 01:42:29.958
that they were savages. . .

805
01:42:31.680 --> 01:42:33.591
but that American soldier. . .

806
01:42:40.800 --> 01:42:42.836
his mother's words. . .

807
01:42:46.600 --> 01:42:48.636
were the same as my mother's.

808
01:42:49.800 --> 01:42:53.634
I want to fulfill my duty
for the general. . .

809
01:42:54.520 --> 01:42:56.590
and our country. . .

810
01:42:58.240 --> 01:43:00.310
but I don't want to die for nothing.

811
01:43:06.080 --> 01:43:07.354
What do you think?

812
01:43:19.080 --> 01:43:20.149
You. . .

813
01:43:21.400 --> 01:43:24.039
haven't lived enough to realize. . .

814
01:43:28.680 --> 01:43:31.035
what you are sacrificing.

815
01:43:39.040 --> 01:43:41.156
Will you surrender with me?

816
01:44:01.720 --> 01:44:02.994
Careful.

817
01:44:06.440 --> 01:44:10.069
They'll notice if we leave together.
You go first.

818
01:44:11.040 --> 01:44:12.712
I'll make up an excuse.

819
01:44:12.880 --> 01:44:15.394
After a while. I'll tell them
I'm going to check on you.

820
01:44:15.560 --> 01:44:17.471
We'll be gone before they even notice.

821
01:44:20.760 --> 01:44:22.716
Pretend that you have dysentery.

822
01:44:23.520 --> 01:44:25.636
Give me your dysentery look.

823
01:44:35.200 --> 01:44:36.792
I guess that'll have to do.

824
01:44:45.400 --> 01:44:46.879
Where are you going?

825
01:44:47.200 --> 01:44:48.792
I've got dysentery.

826
01:44:49.240 --> 01:44:51.071
You're going to surrender. aren't you?

827
01:44:51.240 --> 01:44:53.276
If you are. take me with you.

828
01:44:53.880 --> 01:44:56.348
- I've had enough of this war.
- Be quiet!

829
01:45:04.480 --> 01:45:06.869
Where are you going?

830
01:45:07.120 --> 01:45:09.475
He said he wasn't feeling well.
It could be dysentery.

831
01:45:09.640 --> 01:45:10.868
You two! Stop!

832
01:45:16.400 --> 01:45:17.628
Sir. maybe they got spooked.

833
01:45:34.240 --> 01:45:36.595
Miura. you're on guard.

834
01:45:37.240 --> 01:45:39.151
Make sure we have no more deserters.

835
01:47:01.920 --> 01:47:03.478
What unit were you with?

836
01:47:06.200 --> 01:47:09.909
Higashiyama 314th.

837
01:47:19.240 --> 01:47:20.639
Did you hear. . .

838
01:47:22.240 --> 01:47:25.710
I heard that they would give you a meal.

839
01:47:27.640 --> 01:47:28.789
A meal. . .

840
01:47:32.800 --> 01:47:34.438
That sounds good.

841
01:47:39.240 --> 01:47:40.832
I'm from Yokohama. too.

842
01:47:44.160 --> 01:47:47.311
After this is over. you can come visit me.

843
01:49:00.480 --> 01:49:01.629
Lieutenant!

844
01:49:41.600 --> 01:49:43.318
Let this be a lesson to anyone else. . .

845
01:49:45.440 --> 01:49:47.032
who wants to surrender.

846
01:50:56.960 --> 01:51:00.635
We need to get through the crossfire
to reach the north. . .

847
01:51:01.480 --> 01:51:03.118
and join our forces at the front.

848
01:51:08.920 --> 01:51:09.955
Listen.

849
01:51:11.000 --> 01:51:13.389
We'll head for that cave
and make our way from there.

850
01:51:16.800 --> 01:51:18.279
Don't waste a bullet!

851
01:51:19.400 --> 01:51:20.799
Not a single one.

852
01:51:21.320 --> 01:51:22.833
Don't shoot recklessly.

853
01:52:21.000 --> 01:52:24.913
These are Nishi's troops
and the survivors from Suribachi.

854
01:52:28.840 --> 01:52:30.717
Are there no officers?

855
01:52:34.400 --> 01:52:36.595
You all did a good job making it here.

856
01:52:37.600 --> 01:52:39.192
Fujita. water for them.

857
01:52:43.680 --> 01:52:46.433
I'm sorry. sir. There is no more water.

858
01:52:50.120 --> 01:52:51.189
I'm sorry.

859
01:52:52.480 --> 01:52:53.754
At least you can rest.

860
01:53:08.320 --> 01:53:09.878
You look familiar.

861
01:53:14.880 --> 01:53:16.438
You almost lost your head.

862
01:53:19.360 --> 01:53:23.239
That was the second time you saved me.

863
01:53:25.920 --> 01:53:27.319
The first time. . .

864
01:53:28.000 --> 01:53:31.470
was the day you landed on the island.

865
01:53:35.080 --> 01:53:36.957
Of course. I remember.

866
01:53:38.560 --> 01:53:40.118
Well. everything happens in threes.

867
01:53:56.120 --> 01:53:57.394
Hanako...

868
01:53:58.400 --> 01:54:00.675
<i>This letter will probably
never get to you...</i>

869
01:54:01.360 --> 01:54:02.349
but...

870
01:54:03.040 --> 01:54:05.156
it comforts me to write.

871
01:54:06.560 --> 01:54:08.994
For five days. we've been
without water and food.

872
01:54:10.240 --> 01:54:11.958
<i>To survive...</i>

873
01:54:13.640 --> 01:54:15.631
we do unspeakable things.

874
01:54:18.520 --> 01:54:20.272
<i>There is no escape now.</i>

875
01:54:21.000 --> 01:54:22.115
But...

876
01:54:23.320 --> 01:54:26.039
my only concern is for you and the baby.

877
01:54:32.320 --> 01:54:33.799
Dig up some worms.

878
01:54:52.120 --> 01:54:54.714
<i>The battle is approaching its end...</i>

879
01:54:55.240 --> 01:54:57.879
and there is no more ammunition.
no more water.

880
01:54:58.040 --> 01:55:01.396
All the survivors will engage
in a general attack.

881
01:55:02.680 --> 01:55:05.956
<i>I pray for the victory
and safety of the Empire.</i>

882
01:55:06.560 --> 01:55:08.596
I bid you farewell.

883
01:55:10.200 --> 01:55:14.079
For the country.
I could not fulfill all of my duties.

884
01:55:14.240 --> 01:55:18.028
<i>Now that we have no ammunition.
it is with regret that we must perish.</i>

885
01:55:24.280 --> 01:55:27.317
You made it all the way from Suribachi?

886
01:55:30.080 --> 01:55:32.196
That must have been quite a journey.

887
01:55:37.720 --> 01:55:39.233
You are quite a soldier.

888
01:55:41.480 --> 01:55:42.833
No. sir.

889
01:55:43.840 --> 01:55:45.114
I'm just a simple baker.

890
01:55:45.920 --> 01:55:47.638
You were a baker?

891
01:55:49.080 --> 01:55:50.069
Any family?

892
01:55:51.080 --> 01:55:52.308
A wife. . .

893
01:55:52.920 --> 01:55:57.277
and a baby girl born
last summer in Ohmiya.

894
01:56:00.640 --> 01:56:02.198
I haven't met her yet.

895
01:56:08.200 --> 01:56:09.553
It's strange.

896
01:56:12.000 --> 01:56:15.390
I promised myself to fight
until death for my family. . .

897
01:56:17.240 --> 01:56:21.392
but the thought of my family
makes it difficult to keep that promise.

898
01:56:43.840 --> 01:56:45.717
A radio transmission from the homeland.

899
01:56:58.840 --> 01:57:00.239
<i>For General Kuribayashi...</i>

900
01:57:00.400 --> 01:57:04.598
and his troops. who are fighting bravely
for our country...

901
01:57:04.760 --> 01:57:06.955
<i>a song will be sung by the children
of Nagano...</i>

902
01:57:07.120 --> 01:57:09.156
<i>which is Kuribayashi's hometown.</i>

903
01:57:09.480 --> 01:57:13.439
<i>On the waves of the Pacific</i>

904
01:57:13.600 --> 01:57:16.751
<i>down south from the Imperial City</i>

905
01:57:17.280 --> 01:57:21.751
a small lonely island floats

906
01:57:25.000 --> 01:57:28.470
<i>The fate of our Imperial country</i>

907
01:57:28.640 --> 01:57:33.111
lies in the hands of this island

908
01:57:35.840 --> 01:57:38.354
<i>Iwo Jima</i>

909
01:57:41.760 --> 01:57:45.116
As long as we stand

910
01:57:45.560 --> 01:57:49.473
we shall feel safe. as the Imperial land

911
01:57:49.640 --> 01:57:54.111
shall forever be at peace

912
01:57:57.280 --> 01:58:01.751
We shall fight with pride
and honor at any price

913
01:58:04.040 --> 01:58:07.476
<i>Our proud island</i>

914
01:58:08.040 --> 01:58:10.600
<i>Iwo Jima</i>

915
01:58:32.000 --> 01:58:33.274
Do me a favor.

916
01:58:34.880 --> 01:58:38.509
Stay here and burn all these documents.
and my military chest.

917
01:58:39.640 --> 01:58:41.710
Everything happens in threes.

918
01:59:09.960 --> 01:59:11.916
We will make a general attack.

919
01:59:12.960 --> 01:59:15.190
Although Japan has lost. . .

920
01:59:15.880 --> 01:59:17.677
one day. . .

921
01:59:18.520 --> 01:59:20.556
our people will praise your dedication.

922
01:59:21.640 --> 01:59:25.519
A day will come when they
will weep and pray for your souls.

923
01:59:28.120 --> 01:59:30.315
Be proud to die for your country.

924
01:59:37.160 --> 01:59:39.549
I will always be in front of you.

925
02:02:15.520 --> 02:02:16.714
No more.

926
02:02:18.800 --> 02:02:19.789
No more.

927
02:02:27.520 --> 02:02:29.158
Thank you. Fujita.

928
02:03:00.000 --> 02:03:01.115
This is an order.

929
02:04:06.760 --> 02:04:07.909
You again.

930
02:04:11.240 --> 02:04:14.869
I have one more favor to ask of you.

931
02:04:16.840 --> 02:04:17.989
Bury me. . .

932
02:04:19.080 --> 02:04:20.991
so that no one will find me.

933
02:04:34.960 --> 02:04:35.949
<i>Taro...</i>

934
02:04:36.320 --> 02:04:37.753
I will be home soon.

935
02:04:38.960 --> 02:04:40.871
<i>I'm glad to be going back to Japan...</i>

936
02:04:41.800 --> 02:04:45.076
but I'm a bit sad
to leave my friends behind.

937
02:04:48.400 --> 02:04:49.913
I drove home...

938
02:04:50.960 --> 02:04:51.949
but...

939
02:04:52.360 --> 02:04:54.874
it's lonely driving all by myself.

940
02:05:06.800 --> 02:05:08.711
Is this still Japanese soil?

941
02:05:17.840 --> 02:05:19.512
This is still Japan.

942
02:07:20.720 --> 02:07:21.869
Just put the shovel down.

943
02:08:32.080 --> 02:08:33.149
Be careful.

944
02:14:41.440 --> 02:14:43.431
Subtitles by
SDI Media Group

945
02:14:43.600 --> 02:14:45.591
[ENGLISH]

946
